longest_values: SJCC provides comprehensive case management services, by experienced, multi-lingual case workers and social workers (including those with expertise in immigration issues) and aided by our Computerized Benefits Check Up Program (which assesses eligibility for 41 various entitlement benefit programs and provides application guidance). Our case workers aid clients in obtaining benefits such as Medicaid, Medicare, HEAP, SCRIE, Emergency home repairs, legal assistance, food stamps and translation services among many other services. Our case management team work with our clients to help them obtain services, and to trouble shoot any variety of other issues that may arise in their daily lives.

College Tours – These college tours take students to major colleges and universities around the country.  The recruitment of these students begins in October.  Approximately 48 students and 8 chaperones are in attendance for each tour.  Monthly presentations are given to the group with themes such as; college life, awareness and preparation, financial aid and career exploration.  Other subjects include journal writing and community projects.  Parents are encouraged to attend all meeting leading up to the trip.  During the spring the meeting occur weekly, before the trip which held during the Easter/Spring break (7-14 days)

frequent_values: HMI is seeking 375,000 in Speakers Initiative funding and 10,000 in Member Item Support for our Supportive Services Department, specifically to cover the salaries of our Counselors and Case Managers as we rise to meet a surge in demand for our services (now serving 2,500 young people, over triple our number 4 years ago). The increase in funding from the previous year (100,000) will be to cover all costs associated with hiring an additional Counselor, which will assist us in providing 500 additional young people this year with comprehensive mental health services. Services to be provided include: psychosocial Intake evaluation, individual and group counseling, hot meals (over 10,000 each year), homelessness pantry (clothing, food bags, hot showers, laundry services), family counseling, linkages to onsite HIV/STI/pregnancy testing, and complete wrap!

The grant  will be used to support the NAACP NYC ACT-SO Academic Enrichment Program.  The Program is a free, year-long extracurricular youth development program targeted to African American high-school youth, which provides personalized mentoring, leadership training, and artistic, cultural, technological, and scientific skill development across 26 categories in the arts, humanities, and sciences. Funding will specifically support 2012-13 program expansion, outreach, recruitment, and retention activity and programming throughout the Metro New York area.  Operational goals are a 100 increase in student enrollment and retention; enhanced program content; increased capacity to deliver these services throughout New York City; and to increase public awareness and availability of these resources to high school students. longest_values: Hudson Guildâ€™s Teen Services Program provides services to 150 youth ages 13-24 around education, work and recreation. We assist youth in achieving academic, professional and personal success in a safe, supportive and nurturing environment. The program targets disconnected and at-risk teens and young adults living in Elliott- Chelsea and Fulton Public Housing Developments who either currently experience or are at risk of dropping out of school, being unemployed, engaging in criminal activity or drug/alcohol abuse, and/or live in poverty. The Education component provides access to educational resources focusing on themes of motivation and advocacy, including GED classes, SAT Prep, tutoring, college prep services and trips to visit colleges. The Work component provides opportunities to receive employment by preparing youth through a work readiness curriculum by qualified social workers and a job developer. The Recreation component offers organized physical activities that promote fitness.

Building on the success of the Central Brooklyn Domestic Violence Program (CBDVP), funding wil enable expansion to include a wider number of immigrant victims of domestic violence. Many studies have concluded that immigrant women are at greater risk for serious incidents of domestic violence, including homicide, compared with U.S-born women. That finding combined with additional obstacles to reporting such as immigration status, culture and language barriers, go to producing a highly vulnerable group within the boroughs population. CBDVP has developed a highly successful set of interventions and objectives that seek to address the issues faced by immigrants who experience domestic violence. CBDVP combines community outreach and education activities with direct services to victims of domestic violence. The program has a multi-pronged approach which includes: collaboration with community based immigrant groups, close communication with precinct based DVPOs and allied service providers.

QLS requests 5K to support our work to protect the rights of tenants in Sunnyside, Woodside, Long Island City and Astoria. The QLS Housing Rights Project combats the growing tide of unlawful eviction and harassment of low-income tenants through direct legal services, affirmative litigation, community education and support for tenant organizing. We work closely with community-based organizations, faith-based groups, social service agencies and schools to conduct Know Your Rights clinics and intake programs. The majority of Housing Rights Project clients face barriers due to language, immigration, and/or disability. As more and more corporations expand multifamily housing portfolios in Western Queens, we are witnessing greater numbers of unlawful eviction proceedings and various forms of tenant harassment, including overcharges and lawsuits. The requested funds will directly support client advocacy, community outreach, social service support (where necessary) and materials development.

The proposed children program will offer direct support, advocacy, and counseling to children of battered women among Chinese immigrants in New York City. These children are at a very high risk of developing psychiatric problems, behavioral maladjustments, identity disorders, and harmful conflict resolution skills. GOH Children Counselor will  (1) assess whether the child is a victim of physical, sexual, verbal, and/or psychological abuse himself or herself, (2) coordinate legal, medical, and psychological services to support her/him, (3) foster a therapeutic environment in groups and individual sessions F (4) provide bilingual, age specific, and culturally sensitive  workshops, (5) provide parenting support to assure focused delivery of services to the child, FF (6) coordinate ESL and afterschool classes as academic support, and (7) liaison with schools, shelters, social service agencies, and government entities to coordinate care, support, and services for these high-risk immigrant

LEGAL SERVICES FOR IMMIGRANTS Purpose is to educate and inform immigrant community about making the right choices, culturally appropriate assimilation and enhancing access to essential legal services. The outcome is to improve immigration status of domestic violence victims, torcher victims and persecution based migration through providing in-house direct support toward accessing high quality information and resource services in order to improve their socio-economic and legal status and achieve self-sufficiency. Services are provided in English, French, Spanish, Wolof, Mandingo and other African languages. 1)Assist in Application process and resource materials for Citizenship. 2)Counsel and assist in translation  research for Women, Victims of Torture and Violence under the VAWA, U visa and Asylum programs.3)Collaborate with network on legal forums in pertaining to housing, public benefits and immigration. 4)Print outreach materials for activities and educational materials.
